# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batchoy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn noodle soup may be made from acorns collected from red or white oak species and each oak species gives a distinct flavour.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Ingredient labels do not list from which type of tree acorns are gathered, most likely owing to the large number of oak species and increasing oak hybridization (especially among white oak varieties), which makes it difficult to recognise and document each type of species.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Evidence at Neolithic sites such as Amsa-dong in South Korea show acorns were part of the human diet.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorns contain bitter tannins which would have been leached out to make the acorns edible.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] They were then ground into flour using a saddle quern and milling stone.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] It is unknown exactly where acorn noodles were first produced.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] However, Ogam village, Korea is well known for a long history of acorn cultivation.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] The village's location by the Namhangang River and its mountainous climate and landscape is conducive toward large-scale acorn cultivation.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] The village produces dozens of acorn-based foods, including *dotori kalguksoo* (acorn knife-cut noodles).
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] There are two varieties of acorn noodles: flour-based soba and starch-based vermicelli.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn vermicelli noodles or *dotori naengmyeon* (Korean: 냉면 도토리) are made from acorn starch and some combination of potato, rice, or arrowroot starch, wheat flour, and salt.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] The dried noodles resemble brown plastic threads about 1—1.2 mm in diameter.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Cooked properly and typically eaten cold, acorn-based *naengmyeon* noodles have high elasticity and a chewy consistency.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn soba noodles, or, in Korean, *dotori guksu* (도토리국수), are made from acorn flour and a combination of grain-based flours such as buckwheat and corn, and salt.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] They are about as thick as spaghetti and are used in hot and cold dishes, such as *zaru soba*, in which boiled noodles are served cold with a dipping sauce.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] The Japanese version of these noodles, *donguri-men* (Japanese:どんぐり), typically has less acorn flour than the original Korean version.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Raw acorn noodles are slightly coarser in cut and texture and more brittle than standard buckwheat soba noodles.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Cooked acorn soba noodles are nuttier in flavor and slightly saltier than buckwheat noodles.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] They contain many antioxidants and could be considered an adaptogenic food.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] A common problem among Korean-manufactured products is that their ingredient labels are often not properly translated.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn starch is frequently mislabeled as acorn flour or acorn powder.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] In reality, acorn starch is essentially highly refined acorn flour, devoid of fiber, fat, and almost all nutrition.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] While the acorn itself does indeed contain acorn starch, that starch is not highly refined.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn starch, in contrast, is extracted from the meat of the kernel using a wet process and then dehydrated.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] The heart, or germ, of the kernel is removed and used for producing acorn oil, which is comparable in flavor and quality to olive oil.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] The hull is separated from the kernel meat, and the starch is extracted from the kernel meat.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] It might be more accurate to use the term "acorn meal", although a meal is a coarser, less refined version of flour.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] Both flour- and starch-based acorn noodles are available in upscale Korean markets.
[src:batchoy/acorn-noodle-soup] A few Japanese markets also carry acorn soba noodles, but in general, acorn soba noodles are difficult to find.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Collectively, the fans of a particular object or person constitute its fanbase or fandom.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] They may show their enthusiasm in a variety of ways, such as by promoting the object of their interest, being members of a related fan club, holding or participating in fan conventions or writing fan mail.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] They may also engage in creative activities ("fan labor") such as creating fanzines, writing fan fiction, making memes, drawing fan art, or developing fan games.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Some excessively avid fans are called "**stans**".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Merriam-Webster, the Oxford dictionary and other sources define "fan" as a shortened version of the word *fanatic*.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] *Fanatic* itself, introduced into English around 1550, means "marked by excessive enthusiasm and often intense uncritical devotion".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] It comes from the Modern Latin *fanaticus*, meaning "insanely but divinely inspired".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The word originally pertained to a temple or sacred place [Latin *fanum*, poetic English *fane*].
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The modern sense of "extremely zealous" dates from around 1647; the use of *fanatic* as a noun dates from 1650.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] However, the term "fancy" for an intense liking of something (a usage attested by 1545), while being of a different etymology, coincidentally carries a less intense but somewhat similar connotation to "fanatic".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Use of "the fancy" to mean avid sports enthusiasts emerged as an Americanism in the mid-19th century.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] *The Dickson Baseball Dictionary* cites William Henry Nugent's work asserting that it was derived from *the fancy*, a term referring to the fans of a specific hobby or sport from the early 18th century to the 19th, especially to the followers of boxing.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] According to that theory, it was originally shortened to *fance* then just to the homonym *fans*.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] *The Great American Baseball Scrapbook* attributes the term to Chris von der Ahe, owner of the Saint Louis Brown Stockings in 1882.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Von der Ahe sold tickets for 25 cents, hoping the many patrons would purchase his beer; the low ticket price helped him lead the stats in attendance.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] He called the fanatics filling his stands "fans".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fans usually have a strong enough interest that some even go as far as to make severe changes in their lifestyles in order to accommodate devotion to the focal object.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fans have a desire for external involvement – they are motivated to demonstrate their involvement with the area of interest through certain behaviors (attending conventions, posting online, displaying team banners outside their homes, etc.).
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fans often have a "wish to acquire" material objects related to the area of interest, such as a baseball hit by a famous slugger or a used guitar pick from their musical hero.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] As well, some fans have a desire for social interaction with other fans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This again may take many forms, from casual conversation, e-mail, chat rooms, and electronic mailing lists to regular face-to-face meetings such as fan club meetings and organized conventions.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] There are several groups of fans that can be differentiated by the intensity level of their level of involvement or interest in the hobby (level of fanaticism).
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The likelihood for a subject of interest to be elevated to the level of fandom appears to be dictated by its complexity.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Complexity allows further involvement of fans for a longer period of time because of the time needed to work the subject of interest 'out.' It also contributes to a greater sense of belonging because of the mental effort invested in the subject.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] These fans will often hold a crush on a major movie star, pop star, athlete or celebrity (see teen idol).
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The groupie is an example, a fan of a particular band or musician, who will follow them on concert tours, Another example is Kieran Alderson who has a remarkable love to Formula 1 driver Lando Norris.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The degree of devotion to celebrities can range from a simple crush to the deluded belief that they have a special relationship with the star which does not exist.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In extreme cases, this can lead to celebrity worship syndrome or stalking behavior.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This can easily switch to hatred of the previously loved celebrity, and result in attempts at violent attacks; one notable incident being the death of Rebecca Schaeffer by a stalking fan, Robert John Bardo, in 1989.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The latter is somewhat related to the concept of parasocial interaction where audiences develop one-sided relationships with media personalities and celebrities.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Not all fans have a crush on their idols.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] There are also fans who want to become their friends or respect an idol's relationship.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In fact, there are fans who idolize celebrity couples.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Gaming fans, or "gamers", are fans focused on playing non-sport games, usually role-playing games, board games, miniature wargames, collectible card games or video games.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Music fans can differ somewhat from fans of particular musicians, in that they may focus on a genre of music.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Many of the trade journals around music, such as *Rolling Stone*, were created by music fans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] A notable music fan was groupie Cynthia Plaster Caster, famous for making numerous plaster casts of rock stars' penises.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Another was Pamela Des Barres, author of the book *I'm With The Band*.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In the 1960s, the extreme frenzy of music fans surrounding the Beatles became known as Beatlemania.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In 2019, *Billboard* observed that popular musicians such as Tyler, the Creator had leveraged the power of fans to drive digital downloads using merchandise bundles.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Similarly, *GQ* recognized Vampire Weekend for their commitment to extensive band merchandising for dedicated fans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Popular musicals have their own particular sets of fans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] *Rent* has boasted a sizable number of 'Rentheads' since its Broadway debut.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Similarly, fans devoted to *The Phantom of the Opera* have been dubbed 'Phans'.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In 2018, *Playbill* included *The Phantom of the Opera* in its list of the "Top 10 Musical Fandoms" of the year.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] People who approve of or associate themselves with certain politicians or political groups are generally called "supporters" rather than "fans", although there are politicians with official or unofficial "fan clubs".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Intense and organized support for a politician may be referred to as a personality cult, particularly in authoritarian or totalitarian regimes.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fans of professional wrestling can be divided into two groups: marks and smarks.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Derived from the same term for the prey of conmen, a mark is a fan who believes that everything associated with professional wrestling is real.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In contrast, a "smark" is a fan who recognizes that they are witnessing a stage-managed work ("kayfabe"), but appreciates it nonetheless, including its backstage aspects.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Since the 1920s, an increasingly elaborate sub-culture of organized science fiction fandom has arisen, initially among correspondents to the letter columns of science fiction magazines.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Science fiction fandom developed its own slang, known as fanspeak after the "Newspeak" of the novel *Nineteen Eighty-four*.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fanspeak is made up of acronyms, blended words, obscure in-jokes, puns, coinages from science fiction novels or films, and archaic or standard English words used in specific ways relevant or amusing to the science fiction community.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Some fanspeak terms, like fanzine have become standard English.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Specific sub-groups of science fiction fandom are often known by a collection term.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] A sports fan can be an enthusiast for a particular athlete, team, sport, or all of organized sports as a whole.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Sports fans often attend sporting events in stadiums, in sports bars, or watch them at home on television, and follow news through newspapers, websites, and social media.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The mentality of the sports fan is often such that they will experience a game, or event while living vicariously through players or teams whom the fan favors.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This behavior manifests itself in a number of different ways, depending on the venue.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] At a stadium or arena, sports fans will voice their pleasure with a particular incident, player, or team by cheering, which consists of clapping, fist-pumping, or shouting positive exclamations toward the field of play and ultimately, the favorable object.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Likewise, displeasure toward a particular incident, player, or team may be met by fans with booing, shouting of expletives, and sometimes throwing of objects onto the field.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This violent type of fan reaction is often called hooliganism.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Lighter, more harmless objects are also occasionally thrown onto certain fields of play as a form of celebration of a favorable sports feat.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This is most common when a member of the home team scores a hat trick in hockey.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Other, more mild forms of displeasure shown by sports fans at sporting events involve simple groans of disappointment, and silence.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] These actions often denote that the favored home team is being outperformed by, or has lost to the much less-favored road team.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In North America, extremely enthusiastic fans are often called "superfans": fans who dress up in outrageous and ostentatious costumes or outfits showing their devotion.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fanbases well known for their tenacious love and undying support are called *rabid fans* or fanatics.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] These fans often congregate hours before kickoff in what is known as a tailgation or tailgating.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] At sports bars, sports fans will gather together, often while consuming food and alcoholic beverages, with the purpose of following a particular sporting event on television as a group.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Sports bars often advertise in hopes of drawing fans of a particular player or team to watch together to increase bonds between fans and prevent fights.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This can create the sense of unity in a sports bar as all cheers and boos will appear to be synchronized due to similar feelings and reactions by nearly all fans at the fortunes and misfortunes of the favored team or athlete.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Due to the level of devotion and intensity of feeling towards the favored team or athlete by sports bar patrons, as well as partially due to the alcohol being served, behavior that would be seen as unruly or fanatical outside a sports bar is generally more common inside of one.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The intensity of cheering and jeering at a sports bar by sports fans can often range from equal to stronger than that of fans actually at the sporting event for particularly significant games and matches.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] At home, sports fans may have few fellow fans but also more freedom.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This is sometimes where the most intense cheering or jeering will take place.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Often sports fans will invite other fans of relatively similar rooting intensity over to their house to experience a sporting event together so that all involved can voice pleasure or displeasure to their heart's content and increase shared bonds in the process.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] It is becoming common for this type of bonding to take place over sports-related social networks.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The drivers that make people fans, and in particular sports fans, have been studied by psychologists, such as Dan Wann at Murray State University, and communication scholars, such as Adam Earnheardt at Youngstown State University.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] They attribute people becoming fans to the following factors: One element is entertainment, because sports spectatorship is a form of leisure.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Sports is also a form of escapism, and being a fan gives one an excuse to yell at something, an activity that may be constrained in other areas of one's life.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fan activities give participants a combination of euphoria and stress (about the potential for their team to lose) for which they coin the name "eustress".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fans experience euphoria during moments when play is going well for their team, and stress when play is going against their team.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This tension between the two emotions generates an unusual sense of pleasure or heightened sensations.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Aesthetics are another draw for some fans, who appreciate the precision or skill of play, or of the coordinated movement of the players during a pre-planned "play".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Family bonding is a reason for some fan activities.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Some families watch televised sports on a regular basis and go to sports games as a family outing to watch events and form a psychological bond with one another and as a family.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Others with no biological relations may view the team and fanbase as their family as Arsenal fan Maria Petri stated.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Going to sports events can create a borrowed sense of self-esteem if fans identify with their teams to the extent that they consider themselves to be successful when their teams have been successful (e.g., as seen in the phrase "we have won").
[src:batchoy/aficionados] If a fan identifies strongly with a favorite team, they will respond to the performance of the team as if team success were a personal success and team failure a personal failure.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fangirls and fanboys in fandoms sometimes, with various meanings, consider their fandom to be their "family", and feel very loyal to it, usually.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] According to a study by psychologists from Cambridge University, the more that people publicly express admiration for a public figure, the more likely it is that the fans' faith in the public figure will remain unaffected following "moral violations" by the adored person.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] A **stan** is an excessively avid fan and supporter of a celebrity, television show, group, musical artist, film or film series.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The object of the stan's affection is often called "bias" or "fave".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The term comes from the 2000 song "Stan" by American rapper Eminem, which tells the story of an obsessive and delusional fan.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The term has frequently been used to describe artist devotees whose fanaticism matches the severity of the obsessive character in the song.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The word is sometimes described as a portmanteau of "stalker" and "fan", but this has never been confirmed.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] A website known as "Stan Wars" or "stanipedia" sprouted up to host discussions and flame wars between rival fanbases.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Stan culture has been criticized for being toxic and parasocial.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In South Korea, obsessive fans are known as *sasaengs*.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Colloquially, the term can be used as both a noun or a verb.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Stans of a particular artist are often given more detailed names, such as "Arianators" for fans of Ariana Grande, "Directioner" for fans of One Direction, "Katycats" for fans of Katy Perry, and "Swifties" for fans of Taylor Swift.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Some artists, however, do not have specific titles attributed to their stans; fans of Kylie Minogue have been called Kylie Stans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Even for fandoms with specific titles, the "artist stan" formula still applies.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Some of these monikers are almost universally known and used by fans of the artists as well as outsiders.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The term is not to be confused with Sasaeng fans, which are overly obsessed fans who stalk and sometimes bring harm to idols.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The term was added to the *Oxford English Dictionary* in 2017.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Celebrities have positively reacted to their "stan" followings.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Notably, English singer-songwriter Jessie J had this to say about her stans, "They support me and buy my albums and singles, and they stand outside hotels, and they come to shows, and they get tattoos of my lyrics and they cut their hair like me.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] That's why I call them my Heartbeats, because without them I wouldn't be here".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In 2012, after Jessie J broke her leg, a stan broke her own leg to emulate the injury.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The fan tracked down Jessie J's personal address and sent her a photograph of the self-inflicted injury.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The singer was horrified and decided to increase her security.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Singer-songwriter Lorde has a different opinion on the matter of giving her followers a nickname.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] She discouraged it by saying "I find it grating to lump everyone into a really awkward, pun-centric name" and affirmed she will never name her fanbase.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Women tend to be "more restricted in their leisure choices and opportunities than men," and their experiences within fandoms are typically demeaned to a more sexualized, emotional, or bodily experience, as opposed to intellectual interests.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Due to this, women are rarely given space or voice within the intellectual realm of music.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] According to Frank Zappa, "men come to hear the music and chicks come for the sex thrills," implying that women's involvement in fan communities is purely sexual, and that they are incapable of displaying intellectual or artistic interest in the music itself.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Those who do manage to become involved within the world of 'serious' music are often relegated to the realm of a 'groupie'.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In other words, the term 'groupie' (used synonymously with the term 'fan' or 'fangirl') is frequently used to shame women involved within the music community, restricting their involvement to sexual relations with band members or worshipping male rock stars.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Such discrimination against female fans can become violent at times in an effort to police "authenticity".
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The recent events known as GamerGate provide a good example of such attacks, whereby multiple women working within the gaming industry were victims of sexual harassment and violent threats, some even forced to leave their homes for fear of a physical confrontation.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The fangirls', often stereotyped as female, so-called 'hysteria' is described as the product of sexual repression.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] However, while it is expected for women to be involved in certain fandoms for physical or sexual reasons, this is also viewed as undesirable and driven by hormonal changes.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] These acts of adoration are societally limited to adolescent youth, or menopausal women, in both instances blaming "these two periods of hormonal lunacy" on the irrational, overtly sexual behaviour.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] For instance, Cheryl Cline, in her text entitled "Essays from Bitch: The Women's Rock Newsletter with Bite", discusses how women need to keep their interests hidden once they pass adolescence.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In her own words, "[i]t's a sign of maturity to pack up all the posters, photos, magazines, scrapbooks, and unauthorized biographies you so lovingly collected and shove them in the back of the closet.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] These conflicting accounts of fangirl behaviour are due to the belief that women are not supposed to express such sexual fantasies unless influenced by some hormonal induced craziness, while for men it is normal to be sexual regardless of age.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] According to Jackson Katz in the documentary *Tough Guise 2*, boys are taught early on that to be "real men" they need to be tough and not to show their feelings.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In the predecessor to this documentary, *Tough Guise*, Katz also addresses the issue of body image, using multiple movies, such as *Terminator* and *Rambo*, as well as action figures like G.I.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Joe, to illustrate how 'real men' are defined as big, strong, and muscular.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fanboy portrayals, by definition, do not fit into this mold of a 'real man', with the exception of sports fans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In a study by Gerard Jones on comic book fans, he described the comic book fanboys as "small, anxious, withdrawn, and terrified of the opposite sex." Quite the opposite of the 'real man' previously described by Katz.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Their interests may also be considered as a deviation from societal gender roles, according to Noah Berlastsky, such as playing *Dungeons & Dragons* instead of football.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This lack of traditional masculine traits warrants them much teasing from peers, parental figures, coaches, or older male role models for not conforming to these ideas of masculinity.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] A popular example of such treatment in mainstream media is shown on the sitcom *The Big Bang Theory*, where, multiple times throughout the show's run, the four main characters, portrayed as 'nerdy fanboys', are humiliated by larger 'real men'.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] For instance, in the show pilot, the two main characters, Leonard and Sheldon, get their pants taken by the main female character's ex-boyfriend, who is portrayed as big, strong, tough, confident, and successful with women.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Furthermore, fanboys also deal with issues of gender discrimination in relation to their fandom interests.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] For example, Bronies, a group of young men enthralled by the television show *My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic*, a show typically geared towards young girls, are often the target of ridicule.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Their interest in a 'feminine' media item can be the cause of great shame, causing many to become 'private' bronies, enjoying the show in secret out of fear.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In English, the term "fangirl" typically implies a young female fan.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] The term is often used in a demeaning, derogatory fashion and is said to describe the fans that give "normal" fans a bad name.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In fact, the term "fangirling" is used to describe anyone who obsessively follows a certain fandom to the point where it interferes with their daily lives.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Such a trend of 'authentic' versus 'inauthentic' fan is common within fan communities, and is particularly pertinent to gender discrimination and misogynistic ideals.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] However, on the other hand of the spectrum, some fangirls have embraced the title, considering it a compliment rather than a derogatory term.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In terms of their involvement within fandoms, fangirls are typically portrayed as losing all control, fainting, sobbing, and dashing about in mobs.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] Fanboys are frequently portrayed as "angry nerds", over-aggressive, derogatory, and protective of the object of their obsession, or as bespectacled, geekish, obsessive fans.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] In regards to chosen fandoms, they are typically associated with comic books, video games, science fiction movies or television series, or technology (such as computer or smartphone brands).
[src:batchoy/aficionados] An exception to this portrayal is the sports fan, who is expected to be overtly sexual, and aggressive.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] This portrayal is particularly dominant within the sports arena, which provides a legitimate site for people to act in hypermasculinized ways.
[src:batchoy/aficionados] According to Williams, "Many [men] want to be overtly sexist and racist.
[src:batchoy/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:batchoy/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:batchoy/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:batchoy/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:batchoy/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:batchoy/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] An ***alfajor*** or ***alajú*** (Spanish pronunciation: [alfaˈxoɾ], plural *alfajores*) is a traditional confection.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Originally from present-day Spain, it is found now in Argentina, Bolivia, Southern Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El Salvador, Southern France, Paraguay, Peru, the Philippines, Uruguay, and Venezuela.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The alfajor was born in Iberia during the rule of al-Andalus.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The Spanish alfajor is produced in the form of a small cylinder and is sold either individually or in boxes containing several pieces.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Traditional alfajores in Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn flour joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] More modern "industrial" varieties in Uruguay and Argentina, are coated with dark or white chocolate (many *alfajores* are sold in "black" and "white" versions), or simply covered with powdered sugar.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The word had been introduced into Spanish dictionaries in the 14th century.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] A similar sweet called *alaú* is found in the Arabic-Hispanic cookbook Kitab al-Tabikh, by an anonymous author.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The Spanish grammarian Nebrija noted the word for the first time in his Latin-Spanish Dictionary (1495) as: *alfaxor* or *alaxur*.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In the 12th century, Raimundo Martin describes in his book *Vocabulista* another possible etymology of the Hispano-Arabic *fasur*, meaning "nectar".
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The publication of historical dictionaries of the Spanish language allows one to document both forms of the original *alajur*, written as *alajú* and *alfajor*.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] *Alajur* and multiple geographic variations are sweets made of a paste of almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs and honey.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In the Americas, the word *alfajor* was not known until the 19th century.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In Spain, there are a variety of different recipes for preparing *alfajores*, but the most traditional contain flour, honey, almonds and several spices, such as cinnamon.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] *Alfajores* are most commonly sold around Christmas.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The traditional Spanish *alfajor* has been produced in Medina-Sidonia (where it is called an *alajú*) since ancient times, and the recipe has been traditionally handed down from father to son.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In this town, there is an account of Mariano Pardo de Figueroa, writing under the pen name Dr.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Thebussem, wherein he wrote that on 2 July 1487, Enrique de Guzmán, second count of Medina Sidonia, ordered the council and majors of the region to send to Malaga 50 cows, 50 oxen, 200 calves and provision of *alajú* from his city.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] On 15 September 2004, protected geographical indication was ratified by the *Consejo de agricultura y pesca de la junta de Andalucía* and published in the *Official Journal of the European Union* as *Alfajor de Medina Sidonia* on 6 March 2007.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The regulations of the Andalusian Ministry of Agriculture allow the use of only pure honey, almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs, sugar, flour and spices, such as aniseed, sesame, cilantro, cloves and cinnamon.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] These *alfajores* are meant to be presented in a cylindrical shape, with a minimum weight of 30 grams (1.1 oz) each, and with a minimum size of about 7 centimetres (2.8 in) in length and a diameter of 1.5 centimetres (0.59 in).
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Each of them will be protected with a wrapping paper, and the ends made an ornament in a spiral shape with a ribbon out of the same paper.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Once individually wrapped, they may be packaged in wood or cardboard boxes, but never in plastic.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In the province of Cuenca, Spain, where the *alfajor* is called *alajú,* it is made with almond, honey and figs, wrapped in a wafer.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In Puerto Rico, they underwent creolization, lost their almond and gained ground cassava.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] They can take varying amounts of sugar and spices.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] It is possible that Puerto Rico's most common version of this dessert (the South American version with dulce de leche) reached Puerto Rico from Venezuela, but the opposite is also possible.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Depending on region some add cornstarch, citrus zest, ginger and honey, filled with chocolate, vanilla cream, dulce de leche, fruit paste, or coconut.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The filling can be mixed with almonds, sesame seeds, coconut flakes, or sprinkles.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Traditional "alfajores" in Chile, Argentina,and Uruguay consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn starch joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] These are also known as a *Chilean Oreo*.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] One variation is called "*alfajor de nieve*" (snow alfajor) and has a white coating consisting of a mixture of egg whites and sugar.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Most *alfajores* come packaged in aluminium foil.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Alfajores are made in various diameters and are consumed as snacks.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The *alfajor* has been manufactured and consumed since colonial times in the territories that today belong to Argentina.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The filling is usually dulce de leche, although there are many variations.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] They can be covered with powder sugar (the traditional ones), glazed sugar (Santafesinos or "de nieve"), grated coconut or chocolate.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Argentina is one of the world's largest consumers of alfajores, both in total numbers and in per capita calculations, consuming more than a billion alfajores a year.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] One important Argentine alfajor is the alfajor de Santa Fe or the alfajor santafesino, which has three puff pastry layers adhered to one another with dulce de leche and glazed all over.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] This alfajor is closely linked to the history of the city of Santa Fe.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Colonel Néstor Fernández from Santa Fe took it to the Battle of Caseros in 1851.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] It became so popular with the army that General Justo José de Urquiza had a weekly shipment of these alfajores delivered to his estancia in San José de Entre Ríos.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The production of Santa Fe alfajores began in 1851 in a shop located on the southwest corner of San Jerónimo and 3 de Febrero streets, a few meters from the Cabildo (where the Santa Fe Government House currently stands).
[src:batchoy/alfajor] These alfajores became known throughout the country after the 24 writers of the constitution, who, after living in Santa Fe for six months, took this dessert home as a souvenir.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Today, it is a heritage of the city of Santa Fe and is handcrafted in that city and its surrounding areas.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The nickname "Merengo" gave rise to a brand of alfajores.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The Cordobes alfajor is filled with fruit jellies (generally of quince).
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In addition, there is the Rogel, similar to the Santa Fe but bigger (the size of a small cake) and a variety from Tucuman known as a clarita, with two crunchy cookies and filled with a jelly made up of sugar molasses.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] In Argentina, alfajores made up of cornflour are very consumed as well (covers made up of maize starch, filled with dulce de leche and grated coconut around the filling).
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Mass-production of alfajores traces back to the Atlantic coast of Argentina in the 1950s.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Brands such as Havanna and Balcarce, and as many as 30 others, have been introduced into shops and supermarkets.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Statistics of the year 2021 shows that inhabitants of Argentina consume 6 million alfajores per day.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Two types of alfajores are found in Chile.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The first type of alfajor, similar to the one of corn flour prepared in other countries of Latin America, is prepared over all the territory of Chile, but mainly in the central area of Chile.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] It is known as "candy of corn flour" or, more typically, "chilenitos".
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The chilenitos are manufactured with corn flour or other types of flour and tend to be simpler and smaller than the other alfajores.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The second type of alfajor, considered the true traditional alfajor of the country and known as "chilean alfajor", is mainly prepared in the southern areas of Chile, generally for the patriotic festivities of September.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] It is prepared with two hojarascas (a thin and firm cookie) that, since they are previously baked, acquire a curved form.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] They are adhered to each other with dark brown sugar, panela, manjar or with confectioners cream.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Optionally, they can be garnished in the end of the filling with grated coconut as it is the case of the alfajores filled with manjar or with ground nuts.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Alfajores made their arrival to the Viceroyalty of Peru, the largest administrative district of the Spanish Empire in South America in the 16th century, and have been popular since, especially the artisanal types.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Alfajor de Trujillo is a type of alfajor from Trujillo.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The *alfajor de Trujillo* has several layers and it can be of different sizes and shapes as round or square.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] It is made mainly with products as flour, butter, eggs and milk, filled with milk candy, some pineapple sweet and in some cases peanuts, with cookies within its layers.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The most famous company manufacturing this products in Trujillo is Dulcería Castañeda, which has locations in Trujillo and Lima and has been making them since 1925.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The mass of the alfajor is made of flour, eggs, margarine, salt, and water.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The filling is made with figs, quince, walnuts, blancmange.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] It is one of the products presented in the Gastronomic Fair in Trujillo.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] Another variant of the alfajor de trujillo is King Kong milk candy, which is made in both Trujillo and Lambayeque.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] According to Guinness World Records, the biggest *alfajor* in the world, measuring almost 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in diameter and 80 centimetres (31 in) in height and weighing 464 kilograms (1,023 lb), was made on 11 December 2010 in Minas, Lavalleja Department, Uruguay.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] The giant *alfajor* was made to mark the celebration of Uruguay's first National Alfajor Festival.
[src:batchoy/alfajor] More than 30 people participated in the preparation of the record-breaking *alfajor*.
[src:batchoy/batchoy] The province of Quezon has a variation of the *batsoy Tagalog*, also known as *bombay* or *bumbay* which derives its name from the similarity of the tied banana leaf pouch to the appearance of the turban worn by Sikhs.
[src:batchoy/batchoy] The dish consists of finely chopped and seasoned pork offal wrapped in banana leaf and then boiled in water.
[src:batchoy/batchoy] The dish is served with its cooking broth.
[src:batchoy/batchoy] The Batchoy Festival is an annual food festival held as part of the larger Dinagyang Festival in Iloilo City.
[src:batchoy/batchoy] First held in 2020, it features a friendly competition among aficionados and merchants to determine who offers the best-tasting batchoy.
[src:batchoy/batchoy] The event is a collaboration between SM City Iloilo and the Department of Tourism (DOT), and it is held and celebrated alongside the Grand Iloilo Food Festival at SM City Iloilo Southpoint every January.
